The village of Janbuku, Zaire, is a very pristine piece of land in Central Africa.

In mid-september 1976, a small Church hospital here admitted dozens of similar cases, bleeding from all the orifices and even from their eyes. The nuns and the priest took refuge in a hotel, where visitors were held back by a rope with a sign that read: "Do not enter. Entry may result in death. "

A doctor treating a dying nun took a blood sample to Kinshasa, Zaire, and flew it all the way back to Belgium for virologist Peter Piau. Using an electron microscope, Piau observed a swarm of Serpentine viruses. Until now, virologists had known only another form of the snake like virus, the Marburg virus.

Piau immediately realized that the deadly disease in Zaire could be very catastrophic for humanity. He told the scientists to travel together to Zaire and eventually to the village of Janbuku. Because the history of the virus was transmitted through the fluids of its victims, the outbreak was contained after hospitals were closed and symptomatic people were quarantined, but 318 people died in the plague. To protect his reputation, Piau set his sights on a local river, which he named Ebola.

Ebola disappeared only briefly, returning three years later in Sudan, killing 34 people, and an attack in Gabon in 1994, killing 52.

For the first 37 years of human history, the Zaire ebolavirus always broke out quietly and then died out as the host died or recovered.

In December 2013, Zaire ebolavirus began spreading in a small village in Guinea, infecting more than 28,500 people worldwide and killing more than 11,300, with an average death rate of about 50 percent and as high as 90 percent in parts of Africa, it was also the largest and most complex outbreak of Ebola's disease in history.

Even today, it is difficult to predict with computer accuracy where the next Ebola outbreak will take place, and all that can be done is to improve knowledge of the Zaire ebolavirus through each outbreak.

In Africa, wild animals are a source of meat, especially in the countryside, where Orangutans, monkeys and bats are their main prey. It was in this way that the Zaire ebolavirus repeatedly moved from the jungle to the village and finally to the city.

As an ancient virus, Ebola is still a stranger to us.

The virus that fell from the earth

In early December 2002, Huang Xing, a native of Heyuan City who worked in Shenzhen, felt sick at first, just like a cold, so he went to a nearby clinic and hospital for injections, which had not been good. He was sent to Heyuan People's Hospital 10 days later, his condition worsened and he had difficulty breathing, was taken to the General Hospital of the Guangzhou Military Region.

The disease was not known to humans, initial patient isolation measures were not in place, and many doctors and nurses were infected. Thus, the outbreak of infectious diseases in many countries and regions one after another, and this unexplained infectious disease is called "Atypical pneumonia" , or SARS.

A month later, the University of Hong Kong and the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and prevention isolated the pathogen that caused SARS, which looked like a crown jewel under an electron microscope.

The tiny "crown" then weighed a ton, spreading in just five months from the first outbreak in Guangdong. The worst epidemic of the Early 21st century finally stopped in July 2003, infecting 8,096 people, 774 dead.

Tracing the SARS virus back a decade later, Shi Zhengli, a researcher at the Wuhan Institute of Virology at the Chinese Academy of Sciences, finally traced its natural host to the Chinese rufous Horseshoe Bat.

"although SARS has not made a comeback in so many years, it is still a SARS-like virus that exists in nature. If we humans are not vigilant, it is entirely possible that the next viral infection could be direct or could be transmitted to humans through other animals."

In 2018, Shi spoke of her concerns in a speech in Wuhan. The battle against SARS has been won, and people are still scared about the 17-year-old "war" , but the "away from Venison" has been slowly erased by social psychology. Another thing that Shi did not expect was that "the next time" would come so soon.

At the end of 2019, a new type of pneumonia broke out in Wuhan, the third time that a family of coronaviruses has wreaked havoc on the world since the 21st century. Starting with a wild animal, COVID-19 has made the transition from animal to human in the south China seafood market, much like the SARS outbreak 17 years ago.

"throughout modern history, the killers of humans were smallpox, influenza, tuberculosis, malaria, plague, measles, and cholera, " wrote Jared Diamond, an American biologist, in guns, germs, and steel. They are all infectious diseases that evolved from animal diseases, although it is strange that most of the germs that cause our human epidemics are now almost exclusively human."

An epidemic occurs when an outbreak results in an abnormally high proportion of people in a population, community, or region. The International Health Regulations (IHR) promulgated by the World Health Organization (WHO) aim to protect the world from infectious diseases.

In today's increasingly globalized world, the common fight against the virus is the bounden duty of all mankind.

By contrast, the outbreak of Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) in Saudi Arabia in 2012 is a young disease that is even less well known.

In September 2012, Mers was found in a Qatari patient who had traveled to Saudi Arabia and was treated with respiratory disease, but the disease eventually caused kidney failure and he died 11 days after admission, the cause of the disease is also a new type of coronavirus.

Three years later, Seoul, South Korea, had its first case of foreign migration. In less than a month, there have been more than 100 cases in South Korea, and depending on the history of the disease, a small number of infected patients and patients are in the same ward, infected within five minutes to several hours.

The high rate of MERS transmission in South Korea caught World Health Organization's attention, and by then, 1,142 MERS cases had been reported in 25 countries, resulting in 465 deaths and a mortality rate of 40.7 percent.

The virus has also been traced, eventually to antibodies found in one species of African Bat, and indirectly to the humped camel. Presumably, as trade from North Africa to the Middle East continued, dromedary caravans brought the virus back to the Middle East, infecting more camels and more people through their nasal secretions. There is no vaccine or specific treatment for Mers.

From Ebola to SARS, Mers to pneumonia in Wuhan, it's not just a coincidence that the initial sources of these large-scale infections all seem to point to wildlife.

AIDS, as it is known, has long been known to come from chimpanzees and Cercocebus Atys, and even the flu that everyone has had has come from birds.

In the future, if another virus were to transfer from wild animals to humans, it would probably cause a pandemic, and we still know nothing about the virus that causes it.

From viruses to bacteria

2.1 billion years ago, cells, viruses, and bacteria began to form close connections, and became the three key words in human infectious diseases. With long evolution, some viruses no longer act alone, and they use bacteria to create a lethal combination of "platform opera" .

In 1918, five years into the first world war, Europe was torn apart. At the same time, an invisible virus is beginning to spread around the world. The virus was first reported in Spain, and the outbreak is also known as "Spanish flu" .

There was no technology to develop a vaccine, antibiotics had not yet been discovered, and the disease was out of control. In 1918, the deadliest flu virus in human history, which killed an estimated 50 million people, mysteriously disappeared 18 months later, according to research.

Since 1997, scientists have used the remains of flu victims to obtain the full genome sequence of "Spanish flu" . In 2005, using a reverse genetics system, a flu expert, Ph. D. , performed a reactivation experiment on the virus. In this way, an extinct virus was given new life through the efforts and wisdom of scientists, in a highly protected laboratory, "Pandora's Box" was opened.

Studies have found that the 1918 flu virus does not directly kill, but induces a strong immune response that causes respiratory failure through Streptococcus pneumoniae. Young, healthy adults have stronger immune systems and are often more prone to "cytokine storms, " which explains why young, healthy adults had higher mortality rates during the 1918 flu.

In contrast to the "Spanish flu" virus, which triggers an overreaction in the immune system, the other virus takes the opposite route.

On June 5,1981, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention received a report that four patients in Los Angeles had died of PNEUMOCYSTIS CARINII pneumonia. It's a rare disease, and strangely enough, it has popped up among a peculiar group of people known as the Harvard Gay men.

Just a month later, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention received a report of 26 cases of Kaposi's Sarcoma, all of them gay men. The fact that the disease should occur so frequently in only two out of three million gay people is also highly unusual.

The blood-borne disease, which is caused by an immune deficiency, has been dubbed "Gay Immunodeficiency" without any further scientific explanation.

A few months later, the tables were turned. Similar cases have been found among intravenous drug users, and a growing number of hemophiliacs who have received blood transfusions have also been found to be infected with the disease. The U. S. Centers for Disease Control and prevention finally renamed the disease "Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome" (AIDS) .

A single HIV virus is only 120 nanometers wide and contains nine genes that can make a measly 15 proteins. But it is this virus, whose structure and genetic information are so simple that it can destroy the body's immune system.

Under normal circumstances, when the microorganism invades the human body, will first encounter the human body immune system's resistance. The immune system, the lymphocyte, is an important part of the body's immune system, responsible for blocking the entry of the virus into the immune system, but in the case of HIV, it is powerless.

HIV in the immune system after the invasion of t cells, it will become a puppet factory, and constantly generate new HIV. As the virus increases, the body's immune system is completely defeated, a variety of microorganisms, parasites drive straight into. As a result, serious Opportunistic infection and tumours develop, and AIDS patients eventually die from serious infections or tumours.

Now 30 years later, there is still no effective prevention or treatment, it is in this 30 years time, AIDS has swallowed 30 million people's lives. Currently, there are still 37.9 million people infected with HIV worldwide, and about 770,000 people die each year.

Virus Planet

Carl Zimmer, a scholar at Yale, has written a book, the Virus Planet, in which Karrh writes of viruses: The history of our lives is really a history of viruses.

The number of viruses on earth is also "outrageous. ". For example, when you jump into the ocean and swim, you're swimming in a swarm of viruses.

Scientists have calculated that there are 100 billion virus particles per liter of seawater; in all the oceans of the earth, there are about 10 to the 31st power of virus particles. That's 15 times more than all the fish, shrimp, crabs and other marine life in the ocean combined; the total weight of these viruses is the equivalent of 75 million blue whales, they would be 42 million light-years long, much larger than the entire Milky Way Galaxy.

The virus itself is incredibly small. If you think of each grain of salt as a small cube,. On each edge of the cube, 100 bacteria can be placed side by side, but as many as 1,000 bacteria can be placed side by side. Because of its tiny size, it was discovered more than 200 years after cells and bacteria.

Bacteria are also ubiquitous, often living independently in single-celled forms, and can also live in other organisms. Bacteria are not all harmful, if the bacteria corrosion, the earth may have been "dead everywhere" , if there is no probiotics in the intestinal tract, digestion is difficult.

Viruses are microbes like bacteria, but they can only grow inside living things. Once the virus enters the body, it targets healthy cells, lures them into a strike and creates more viruses. Although they are called "viruses" , their effects go far beyond making people sick. Bacteriophages, known as "bacterial viruses" , invade and kill specific bacteria, and human retrovirus play an important role in the genetic process.

Diseases caused by bacteria are now more treatable than those caused by viruses. But until antibiotics were discovered, there was no effective treatment for bacterial infections in humans. The hospital was full of patients with cuts and cuts and septicemia, and doctors were at a loss to observe, hoping that the patients would survive on their own.

In fact, bacteria once caused a major plague that spread from person to person.

The 1346, a Mongol army that believed in steel swords and steeds, rode into a city in a Black Sea port. As the siege continued, a furious Genghis Khan ordered the bodies of those infected with the plague to be thrown into the city by a trebuchet. The people in the city did not know about the plague and did not care about the bodies that were thrown in. As the bodies decomposed, a terrible plague swept over them.

People do their best to avoid death, they pray to God, eat good meat, drink good wine... The doctors tried everything from purging to bleeding, to smoking, to cauterizing lymph nodes, to rubbing them with dried toad fluid, to no avail.

Doctor Beak was a physician from the black death. They would wear beaked masks with anti-infective properties to treat patients. These plague doctors often had little medical training and lacked clinical diagnostic skills, but because of the shortage of manpower in Europe, these doctors, in turn, have become a valuable asset to towns and cities.

They often wore robes and used a wooden crutch to touch patients for treatment. It was also used to scourge the sick to absolve them of their sins, for it was believed that the black death was an unblessed evil, and that only by flogging could the sick be saved from divine punishment.

Before long, the black death was everywhere in Europe, and the funeral bells were ringing out for the new dead. The Danish ALMANAC first described the event as "black" , not just because the patient's skin was blackened by subcutaneous bleeding in the later stages, but more precisely because of the dark, horrible shadow it cast.

"pedestrians walk down the street and die suddenly; those who stay at home die alone, unknown until their stench is smelled; bodies are taken daily and hourly outside the city; cows roam the streets of the city and no one is seen... " boccaccio's Florence has become a living hell.

The black death could erupt in medieval Europe largely because of poverty and squalor, the indiscriminate disposal of rubbish in cities, and the contamination of drinking water with domestic sewage. That all began to change with the industrial revolution, people got rich, urban public health systems were perfected, and the black death finally ended after a hundred years.

The black death killed an estimated 25 million people worldwide and profoundly changed human history. England was particularly devastated by the epidemic, because England had a smaller population, one million people were killed by the black death, when the total population of England was just over four million, the famous hundred years'war between Britain and France was brought to a halt by the plague.

When the first antibiotics were discovered, more than 500 years after the black death, the most effective way to treat bacterial infections emerged. At the same time, humans pay a price for interfering with the natural order of things: some bacteria develop resistance and pass it on to their offspring, eventually becoming "superbugs" .

Drug-resistant "superbugs" infect 2.8 million people and kill more than 35,000 a year, according to a new report from the CDC, highlighting a huge new threat to public health, the CDC calls it the "post-antibiotic era. ".

Through A long-term struggle against bacteria and viruses, humans have evolved three lines of defense for the immune system: the First Line of Defense is made up of skin and mucous membranes and their secretions; A third line of defense consisting of the immune organs (tonsils, lymph nodes, thymus, bone marrow, and spleen) and immune cells (lymphocyte, monocytes / macrophages, granulocytes, mast cells) through the circulation of blood and lymph.

It is these three lines of defense that have helped humans resist most viruses and bacteria, and the immune system "remembers" these microbes from the moment a baby is born, in the fight against some of the causes of disease in the human body will produce antibodies and lifelong immunity.

Vaccines Work by mimicking the process by which bacteria or viruses enter the body, thereby activating our immune system, which is usually composed of viruses that are not infectious.

How do humans fight drugs?

If there's anything that could kill tens of millions of people over the next few decades, it's probably a highly contagious virus, because we're investing very little in systems to prevent it, Bill Gates once said in a speech, we are not ready to prevent a pandemic.

In the face of new virus-induced infectious diseases, people's first instinct is to rely on the development of specific drugs and vaccines. However, unfortunately, targeted at a new virus specific drugs and vaccines in a short period of time is difficult to play a larger role. Whether or not specific drugs and vaccines work in humans, it will take a long time for drugs and vaccines to be developed from initiation to production.

SARS broke out in Guangdong in late 2002 and was gradually brought under control seven months later. The SARS vaccine was launched in the spring of 2004 and formally completed in 2006. At that time, SARS had disappeared. Since 1987, the United States has launched the first clinical trial of an AIDS vaccine. But in the 30 years since then, the world has developed more than 40 AIDS vaccines, but not a vaccine worth the market.

The same is true of drug development, even when applied to the actual treatment process often only plays a supporting role. For All kinds of new viruses, no specific drugs have been found so far, the treatment process can only be assisted by inhalation, anti-infection, replenish body fluids and other methods to maintain the survival of patients, and then wait for the patient's own immune system to eliminate the invading virus, the same is true of the treatment of pneumonia in Wuhan today.

In the face of such a sudden outbreak of infectious disease, the ancient but exceptionally effective method is isolation. From the siege of 1374 against the bubonic plague, to the 1910 railway shutdown of Wu Lien-teh to the great plague of Manchuria, to the present siege of Wuhan against the new coronavirus pneumonia, isolation has played a crucial role.
The core of isolation has three: First, to find and manage the source of infection. For example, if the virus is found to have human-to-human characteristics, the disease or suspected patients can be quickly identified and isolated treatment can quickly control the epidemic. The second is to cut off the means of transmission. SARS and pneumonia in Wuhan were spread by droplets. Avoiding large-scale gathering of people and long-distance Movement of people would help to cut off the transmission route. The third is to protect vulnerable groups. At the beginning of the outbreak of pneumonia in Wuhan, the elderly due to the decline of their own immune system become susceptible to the crowd, the degree of attention is relatively higher.

Read the above three points, we can also understand why the country in the fight against the new coronavirus decisive medical isolation, blockade of traffic and other measures and called for all to wear masks.

The root of the outbreak lies in its infectivity. Su Yiren, a virus expert in Taiwan who was involved in the fight against SARS, pointed out that these viruses also follow a common law: the higher the fatality rate, the lower the infection rate, for example, the death rate after Zaire ebolavirus infection is as high as 90% , but the possibility of transmission is extremely low; the SARS virus is highly infectious after the onset of disease, but the mortality rate is low.

The spread of the virus is highly dependent on individual contact, and if a person infected with an infectious disease can not spread to more than one person, the disease will disappear on its own over time. To measure the spread of the virus, a relatively simple quantitative indicator, called the Basic reproduction number, has been developed, which means that an infected person can, on average, infect several people without intervention. The most common measles, RO, is between 12 and 18, smallpox is between 3.5 and 7, influenza is between 2 and 4, and SARS 17 years ago was between 2 and 5.

Recently, published in the Journal of the The New England Journal of Medicine, the dynamics of the initial transmission of pneumonia in Wuhan, China, the paper estimated that the RO value of pneumonia in Wuhan was less than 2.2, based on the data of the first 425 confirmed cases.

Misunderstandings and rumors

With the continued spread of pneumonia in Wuhan, the development of the epidemic has become a topic of public concern, people always pay attention to the authoritative media reports, but also received some can be described as "rumors" of the gossip. The virus spreads, the rumor spreads, the virus injures the lung, the erroneous zone and the rumor actually are disturbing the human heart.

On January 20, a screenshot went viral on facebook saying that almost no smokers died of SARS in China during the SARS epidemic. The smoke is nanoscale, the soot covers the surface of the lung cells, giving each cell the equivalent of a human nano mask, which is finer and denser than the Micron K90 mask, blocking the virus from attaching and entering, cutting off the roots.

Industry experts have since come forward to correct this view. Although there has been a slight increase in the proportion of non-smokers suffering from SARS, there is no statistically significant difference and smoking is not a way to ward off the virus. On the contrary, smoking often leads to chronic bronchitis, bronchitis, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, which in turn leads to more infections.

On January 25, a chat thread began circulating on Wechat, with the presenter explaining the principles of viruses, bacteria and cancer from the point of view of a tech man and declaring that he wanted to "avoid panic" . Luo NIANCI, director of the China Resources JCI Hospital Management Research Institute, then corrected some of the misleading information in the records.

"Tech Man" said: There are only a few super bacteria, human beings have no way, but can also be treated through a variety of antibiotics at the same time, as long as the bacterial infection has not led to massive organ necrosis, no one's GONNA get killed.

The problem with bacteria, says Luo NIANCI, is that large numbers of drug resistant superbugs like Mrsa and Vre kill hundreds of thousands of people every year, and almost all of humanity's next generation of antibiotics have failed in the last 20 years, so by 2050, it's estimated, 10 million people die every year from superbugs. Therefore, the bacterial threat is a real and serious threat to human life.

Luo NIANCI also has a different view on the "science man" : "Once left the host body, (the virus) will die within minutes or even seconds" , he said: "It is even more misleading to say that the virus can live for more than 24 hours in dry places such as elevator buttons and door knobs, and for longer periods in wet places, which is why people need to wear masks and wash their hands frequently. In 70% of cases, when a person coughs or sneezes and droplets carry the virus into physical space, the healthy person's hands come into contact with the virus and then touch the mucous membranes of their eyes, nose and mouth, causing the virus to invade and infect them."

In fact, whether the virus is an organic organism is still under discussion, and it is very different from the structure of cells. A cell contains many Organelles, but a virus contains only two or three components. The structure can be summed up as: a protein coat contains genetic material (DNA or RNA) .

The virus also spreads in a variety of ways, with animal viruses transmitted by Mosquito Bites; influenza viruses can be transmitted by coughing and sneezing; HIV and Ebola can be transmitted by contact with body fluids; Hand, foot and Mouth Disease (HFMD) viruses can be transmitted by infected hands, food and water.

"Science Man" also stressed that the railings will not spread the virus: "unless the previous carrier just touched the railings, within a few seconds we touch the railings, and contact the hands just have wounds, the virus has a one-in-10,000 chance of invasion from here

In fact, as early as 2016, several scientists at CDC laboratories in the United States conducted rigorous experiments and found that influenza viruses proved to survive on stainless steel surfaces for up to seven days and remain infectious.

The virus is not as "science and technology men" said, "once infected with the virus, there is currently no medicine. ". Luo NIANCI in the process of refuting the anti-hepatitis C Virus Drug Gila (Lee) de. On December 6,2013, Gilead I was launched in the United States, and the development of new drugs for Hepatitis C was also on the fast track. In 2014, Gilead II had a cure rate of 95 percent for Hepatitis C, on May 16,2017, Mylan Ji III, which went on sale in India, had a cure rate of more than 99% .

Living on a virus-ridden planet is a fact and will depend on it for a long time to come, but we should think more deeply in the bleeding history of human resistance.

From Ebola in central Africa 40 years ago to pneumonia in Wuhan today, in the face of an unpredictable outbreak of disease, in a natural sense, these diseases often occur because we have upset a certain balance.

There is a book called the age of Comorbidity, which tells the story of disease "shared" between animals and humans. "We have a long and profound relationship with animals, " the authors write, "and both doctors and patients have to think beyond the confines of beds to farmhouses, jungles, oceans and skies. "

Perhaps from today's point of view, these viruses can "fall off the earth" is not only doctors and patients need to think about the problem, but all due reflection.

If not, we'll soon be stuck with a fourth coronavirus.

From viruses to bacteria

From viruses to bacteria

2.1 billion years ago, cells, viruses, and bacteria began to form close connections, and became the three key words in human infectious diseases. With long evolution, some viruses no longer act alone, and they use bacteria to create a lethal combination of "platform opera" .

In 1918, five years into the first world war, Europe was torn apart. At the same time, an invisible virus is beginning to spread around the world. The virus was first reported in Spain, and the outbreak is also known as "Spanish flu" .

There was no technology to develop a vaccine, antibiotics had not yet been discovered, and the disease was out of control. In 1918, the deadliest flu virus in human history, which killed an estimated 50 million people, mysteriously disappeared 18 months later, according to research.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Since 1997, scientists have used the remains of flu victims to obtain the full genome sequence of "Spanish flu" . In 2005, using a reverse genetics system, a flu expert, Ph. D. , performed a reactivation experiment on the virus. In this way, an extinct virus was given new life through the efforts and wisdom of scientists, in a highly protected laboratory, "Pandora's Box" was opened.

Studies have found that the 1918 flu virus does not directly kill, but induces a strong immune response that causes respiratory failure through Streptococcus pneumoniae. Young, healthy adults have stronger immune systems and are often more prone to "cytokine storms, " which explains why young, healthy adults had higher mortality rates during the 1918 flu.

In contrast to the "Spanish flu" virus, which triggers an overreaction in the immune system, the other virus takes the opposite route.

On June 5,1981, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention received a report that four patients in Los Angeles had died of PNEUMOCYSTIS CARINII pneumonia. It's a rare disease, and strangely enough, it has popped up among a peculiar group of people known as the Harvard Gay men.

Just a month later, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention received a report of 26 cases of Kaposi's Sarcoma, all of them gay men. The fact that the disease should occur so frequently in only two out of three million gay people is also highly unusual.

The blood-borne disease, which is caused by an immune deficiency, has been dubbed "Gay Immunodeficiency" without any further scientific explanation.

A few months later, the tables were turned. Similar cases have been found among intravenous drug users, and a growing number of hemophiliacs who have received blood transfusions have also been found to be infected with the disease. The U. S. Centers for Disease Control and prevention finally renamed the disease "Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome" (AIDS) .

A single HIV virus is only 120 nanometers wide and contains nine genes that can make a measly 15 proteins. But it is this virus, whose structure and genetic information are so simple that it can destroy the body's immune system.

Under normal circumstances, when the microorganism invades the human body, will first encounter the human body immune system's resistance. The immune system, the lymphocyte, is an important part of the body's immune system, responsible for blocking the entry of the virus into the immune system, but in the case of HIV, it is powerless.

HIV in the immune system after the invasion of t cells, it will become a puppet factory, and constantly generate new HIV. As the virus increases, the body's immune system is completely defeated, a variety of microorganisms, parasites drive straight into. As a result, serious Opportunistic infection and tumours develop, and AIDS patients eventually die from serious infections or tumours.

Now 30 years later, there is still no effective prevention or treatment, it is in this 30 years time, AIDS has swallowed 30 million people's lives. Currently, there are still 37.9 million people infected with HIV worldwide, and about 770,000 people die each year.

Virus Planet

Carl Zimmer, a scholar at Yale, has written a book, the Virus Planet, in which Karrh writes of viruses: The history of our lives is really a history of viruses.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The number of viruses on earth is also "outrageous. ". For example, when you jump into the ocean and swim, you're swimming in a swarm of viruses.

Scientists have calculated that there are 100 billion virus particles per liter of seawater; in all the oceans of the earth, there are about 10 to the 31st power of virus particles. That's 15 times more than all the fish, shrimp, crabs and other marine life in the ocean combined; the total weight of these viruses is the equivalent of 75 million blue whales, they would be 42 million light-years long, much larger than the entire Milky Way Galaxy.

The virus itself is incredibly small. If you think of each grain of salt as a small cube,. On each edge of the cube, 100 bacteria can be placed side by side, but as many as 1,000 bacteria can be placed side by side. Because of its tiny size, it was discovered more than 200 years after cells and bacteria.

Bacteria are also ubiquitous, often living independently in single-celled forms, and can also live in other organisms. Bacteria are not all harmful, if the bacteria corrosion, the earth may have been "dead everywhere" , if there is no probiotics in the intestinal tract, digestion is difficult.

Viruses are microbes like bacteria, but they can only grow inside living things. Once the virus enters the body, it targets healthy cells, lures them into a strike and creates more viruses. Although they are called "viruses" , their effects go far beyond making people sick. Bacteriophages, known as "bacterial viruses" , invade and kill specific bacteria, and human retrovirus play an important role in the genetic process.

Diseases caused by bacteria are now more treatable than those caused by viruses. But until antibiotics were discovered, there was no effective treatment for bacterial infections in humans. The hospital was full of patients with cuts and cuts and septicemia, and doctors were at a loss to observe, hoping that the patients would survive on their own.

In fact, bacteria once caused a major plague that spread from person to person.

The 1346, a Mongol army that believed in steel swords and steeds, rode into a city in a Black Sea port. As the siege continued, a furious Genghis Khan ordered the bodies of those infected with the plague to be thrown into the city by a trebuchet. The people in the city did not know about the plague and did not care about the bodies that were thrown in. As the bodies decomposed, a terrible plague swept over them.

People do their best to avoid death, they pray to God, eat good meat, drink good wine... The doctors tried everything from purging to bleeding, to smoking, to cauterizing lymph nodes, to rubbing them with dried toad fluid, to no avail.

Doctor Beak was a physician from the black death. They would wear beaked masks with anti-infective properties to treat patients. These plague doctors often had little medical training and lacked clinical diagnostic skills, but because of the shortage of manpower in Europe, these doctors, in turn, have become a valuable asset to towns and cities.

The black death could erupt in medieval Europe largely because of poverty and squalor, the indiscriminate disposal of rubbish in cities, and the contamination of drinking water with domestic sewage. The black death killed an estimated 25 million people worldwide and profoundly changed human history. England was particularly devastated by the epidemic, because England had a smaller population, one million people were killed by the black death, when the total population of England was just over four million, the famous hundred years'war between Britain and France was brought to a halt by the plague.

When the first antibiotics were discovered, more than 500 years after the black death, the most effective way to treat bacterial infections emerged. At the same time, humans pay a price for interfering with the natural order of things: some bacteria develop resistance and pass it on to their offspring, eventually becoming "superbugs" .

Drug-resistant "superbugs" infect 2.8 million people and kill more than 35,000 a year, according to a new report from the CDC, highlighting a huge new threat to public health, the CDC calls it the "post-antibiotic era. ".

How do humans fight drugs?

If there's anything that could kill tens of millions of people over the next few decades, it's probably a highly contagious virus, because we're investing very little in systems to prevent it, Bill Gates once said in a speech, we are not ready to prevent a pandemic.

In the face of new virus-induced infectious diseases, people's first instinct is to rely on the development of specific drugs and vaccines. However, unfortunately, targeted at a new virus specific drugs and vaccines in a short period of time is difficult to play a larger role. Whether or not specific drugs and vaccines work in humans, it will take a long time for drugs and vaccines to be developed from initiation to production.

SARS broke out in Guangdong in late 2002 and was gradually brought under control seven months later. The SARS vaccine was launched in the spring of 2004 and formally completed in 2006. At that time, SARS had disappeared. Since 1987, the United States has launched the first clinical trial of an AIDS vaccine. But in the 30 years since then, the world has developed more than 40 AIDS vaccines, but not a vaccine worth the market.

The same is true of drug development, even when applied to the actual treatment process often only plays a supporting role. For All kinds of new viruses, no specific drugs have been found so far, the treatment process can only be assisted by inhalation, anti-infection, replenish body fluids and other methods to maintain the survival of patients, and then wait for the patient's own immune system to eliminate the invading virus, the same is true of the treatment of pneumonia in Wuhan today.

In the face of such a sudden outbreak of infectious disease, the ancient but exceptionally effective method is isolation. From the siege of 1374 against the bubonic plague, to the 1910 railway shutdown of Wu Lien-teh to the great plague of Manchuria, to the present siege of Wuhan against the new coronavirus pneumonia, isolation has played a crucial role.
The core of isolation has three: First, to find and manage the source of infection. For example, if the virus is found to have human-to-human characteristics, the disease or suspected patients can be quickly identified and isolated treatment can quickly control the epidemic. The second is to cut off the means of transmission. SARS and pneumonia in Wuhan were spread by droplets. Avoiding large-scale gathering of people and long-distance Movement of people would help to cut off the transmission route. The third is to protect vulnerable groups. At the beginning of the outbreak of pneumonia in Wuhan, the elderly due to the decline of their own immune system become susceptible to the crowd, the degree of attention is relatively higher.

Read the above three points, we can also understand why the country in the fight against the new coronavirus decisive medical isolation, blockade of traffic and other measures and called for all to wear masks.

The root of the outbreak lies in its infectivity. Su Yiren, a virus expert in Taiwan who was involved in the fight against SARS, pointed out that these viruses also follow a common law: the higher the fatality rate, the lower the infection rate, for example, the death rate after Zaire ebolavirus infection is as high as 90% , but the possibility of transmission is extremely low; the SARS virus is highly infectious after the onset of disease, but the mortality rate is low.

The spread of the virus is highly dependent on individual contact, and if a person infected with an infectious disease can not spread to more than one person, the disease will disappear on its own over time. To measure the spread of the virus, a relatively simple quantitative indicator, called the Basic reproduction number, has been developed, which means that an infected person can, on average, infect several people without intervention. The most common measles, RO, is between 12 and 18, smallpox is between 3.5 and 7, influenza is between 2 and 4, and SARS 17 years ago was between 2 and 5.

Misunderstandings and rumors

With the continued spread of pneumonia in Wuhan, the development of the epidemic has become a topic of public concern, people always pay attention to the authoritative media reports, but also received some can be described as "rumors" of the gossip. The virus spreads, the rumor spreads, the virus injures the lung, the erroneous zone and the rumor actually are disturbing the human heart.

On January 20, a screenshot went viral on facebook saying that almost no smokers died of SARS in China during the SARS epidemic. The smoke is nanoscale, the soot covers the surface of the lung cells, giving each cell the equivalent of a human nano mask, which is finer and denser than the Micron K90 mask, blocking the virus from attaching and entering, cutting off the roots.

Industry experts have since come forward to correct this view. Although there has been a slight increase in the proportion of non-smokers suffering from SARS, there is no statistically significant difference and smoking is not a way to ward off the virus. On the contrary, smoking often leads to chronic bronchitis, bronchitis, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, which in turn leads to more infections.

On January 25, a chat thread began circulating on Wechat, with the presenter explaining the principles of viruses, bacteria and cancer from the point of view of a tech man and declaring that he wanted to "avoid panic" . Luo NIANCI, director of the China Resources JCI Hospital Management Research Institute, then corrected some of the misleading information in the records.

With the continued spread of pneumonia in Wuhan, the development of the epidemic has become a topic of public concern, people always pay attention to the authoritative media reports, but also received some can be described as "rumors" of the gossip. The virus spreads, the rumor spreads, the virus injures the lung, the erroneous zone and the rumor actually are disturbing the human heart.

On January 20, a screenshot went viral on facebook saying that almost no smokers died of SARS in China during the SARS epidemic. The smoke is nanoscale, the soot covers the surface of the lung cells, giving each cell the equivalent of a human nano mask, which is finer and denser than the Micron K90 mask, blocking the virus from attaching and entering, cutting off the roots.

Industry experts have since come forward to correct this view. Although there has been a slight increase in the proportion of non-smokers suffering from SARS, there is no statistically significant difference and smoking is not a way to ward off the virus. On the contrary, smoking often leads to chronic bronchitis, bronchitis, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, which in turn leads to more infections.

On January 25, a chat thread began circulating on Wechat, with the presenter explaining the principles of viruses, bacteria and cancer from the point of view of a tech man and declaring that he wanted to "avoid panic" . Luo NIANCI, director of the China Resources JCI Hospital Management Research Institute, then corrected some of the misleading information in the records.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"Tech Man" said: There are only a few super bacteria, human beings have no way, but can also be treated through a variety of antibiotics at the same time, as long as the bacterial infection has not led to massive organ necrosis, no one's GONNA get killed.

The problem with bacteria, says Luo NIANCI, is that large numbers of drug resistant superbugs like Mrsa and Vre kill hundreds of thousands of people every year, and almost all of humanity's next generation of antibiotics have failed in the last 20 years, so by 2050, it's estimated, 10 million people die every year from superbugs. Therefore, the bacterial threat is a real and serious threat to human life.

Luo NIANCI also has a different view on the "science man" : "Once left the host body, (the virus) will die within minutes or even seconds" , he said: "It is even more misleading to say that the virus can live for more than 24 hours in dry places such as elevator buttons and door knobs, and for longer periods in wet places, which is why people need to wear masks and wash their hands frequently. In 70% of cases, when a person coughs or sneezes and droplets carry the virus into physical space, the healthy person's hands come into contact with the virus and then touch the mucous membranes of their eyes, nose and mouth, causing the virus to invade and infect them."

In fact, whether the virus is an organic organism is still under discussion, and it is very different from the structure of cells. A cell contains many Organelles, but a virus contains only two or three components. The structure can be summed up as: a protein coat contains genetic material (DNA or RNA) .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The virus also spreads in a variety of ways, with animal viruses transmitted by Mosquito Bites; influenza viruses can be transmitted by coughing and sneezing; HIV and Ebola can be transmitted by contact with body fluids; Hand, foot and Mouth Disease (HFMD) viruses can be transmitted by infected hands, food and water.

"Science Man" also stressed that the railings will not spread the virus: "unless the previous carrier just touched the railings, within a few seconds we touch the railings, and contact the hands just have wounds, the virus has a one-in-10,000 chance of invasion from here

In fact, as early as 2016, several scientists at CDC laboratories in the United States conducted rigorous experiments and found that influenza viruses proved to survive on stainless steel surfaces for up to seven days and remain infectious.

The virus is not as "science and technology men" said, "once infected with the virus, there is currently no medicine. ". Luo NIANCI in the process of refuting the anti-hepatitis C Virus Drug Gila (Lee) de. On December 6,2013, Gilead I was launched in the United States, and the development of new drugs for Hepatitis C was also on the fast track. In 2014, Gilead II had a cure rate of 95 percent for Hepatitis C, on May 16,2017, Mylan Ji III, which went on sale in India, had a cure rate of more than 99% .

Living on a virus-ridden planet is a fact and will depend on it for a long time to come, but we should think more deeply in the bleeding history of human resistance.

From Ebola in central Africa 40 years ago to pneumonia in Wuhan today, in the face of an unpredictable outbreak of disease, in a natural sense, these diseases often occur because we have upset a certain balance.

There is a book called the age of Comorbidity, which tells the story of disease "shared" between animals and humans. "We have a long and profound relationship with animals, " the authors write, "and both doctors and patients have to think beyond the confines of beds to farmhouses, jungles, oceans and skies. "

Perhaps from today's point of view, these viruses can "fall off the earth" is not only doctors and patients need to think about the problem, but all due reflection.

If not, we'll soon be stuck with a fourth coronavirus.
